# Prisma Migration Rules — ALWAYS Follow

## RULE #1: Every schema change MUST have a migration file

**No exceptions.** If you add, remove, or rename any field, model, or enum in `schema.prisma`, you MUST create a migration file before committing.

```bash
cd apps/web
npx prisma migrate dev --name <describe-your-change>
```

Then commit BOTH files together — never commit schema.prisma alone:

```bash
git add prisma/schema.prisma prisma/migrations/
git commit -m "feat: add widgetSuggestedQuestions to Bot"
```

## RULE #2: Never push schema.prisma without a migration

The CI/CD pipeline will **block the deployment** if `schema.prisma` changed but no migration file was added in the same commit. You will get this error:

```
❌ ERROR: schema.prisma was changed but no migration file was committed.
   Fix: cd apps/web && npx prisma migrate dev --name <describe-your-change>
```

## RULE #3: Renaming or removing columns = 3 separate deploys

Never rename or drop a column in one deploy — it crashes the running app.

| Deploy | Action |
|--------|--------|
| 1st | Add the new column |
| 2nd | Migrate existing data to new column |
| 3rd | Remove the old column |

## RULE #4: New env variables need server update too

If you add `process.env.NEW_VAR` to the code:
1. Add it to `/var/www/secrets/.env` on the Droplet **before** pushing
2. Add it to `.env.example` in the repo
3. Never commit real secret values to git

## What the CI/CD pipeline checks on every push

| Check | Blocks deploy if... |
|-------|-------------------|
| TypeScript | Any type errors exist |
| Migration guard | schema.prisma changed without a new migration file |
| Health check | App returns non-200 from `/api/health` after deploy |
